# Comms architecture (ThreejsClient)

## Reference stack

| Concern | Reference |
|---------|-----------|
| Inbound decode / routing | **Bevy** (`Rfc4Router`, `crates/comms`) |
| Outbound movement & profile | **Unity Foundation Client** — `RFC4_PROTOCOL_VERSION` in `Packet` header (`dclRfc4Comms.ts`) |
| Outbound LiveKit **text chat** | **dcl-companion** — `sdk7/dcl-companion/web-app-social/src/dclRfc4Chat.ts` + `publishData(..., { reliable: true })` |
| LiveKit session wiring | **dcl-companion** — `livekitRoom.ts`, `JumpInView` / `PublicSceneStreamPage` |

## Outbound chat (critical)

Unity movement-style `Packet.encode({ protocolVersion: 100, … chat })` does **not** deliver on LiveKit scene rooms in practice.

Use **`encodeRfc4ChatPacket` in `src/social/dclRfc4Chat.ts`** — byte-compatible with dcl-companion:

- `Chat.timestamp` = session elapsed seconds since LiveKit connect
- Trailing protobuf field `11` = protocol version `100`
- Publish to every connected chat transport: scene room, world room, and island (when connected)

Local UI display time: `Date.now() / 1000` (not the wire timestamp).

## Do not

- Mention or target a Godot explorer comms parity path in this repo.
- Use Unity header encode for LiveKit chat until verified end-to-end on wire.
